HEADWORD: Hole
<hw>Hole</hw> <pr>(h⟦omac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Whole.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hole</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hole
<hw>Hole</hw> <pr>(h⟦omac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hol</ets>, <ets>hole</ets>, AS. <ets>hol</ets>, hole, cavern, from
<ets>hol</ets>, a., <ets>hollow</ets>; akin to D. <ets>hol</ets>, OHG.
<ets>hol</ets>, G. <ets>hohl</ets>, Dan. <ets>huul</ets> hollow,
<ets>hul</ets> hole, Sw. <ets>h⟦aring⟧l</ets>, Icel. <ets>hola</ets>;
prob. from the root of AS. <ets>helan</ets> to conceal. See
<er>Hele</er>, <er>Hell</er>, and cf. <er>Hold</er> of a ship.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A hollow place or cavity; an excavation; a pit; an
opening in or through a solid body, a fabric, etc.; a perforation; a
rent; a fissure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>holes</qex> where eyes should be.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The blind walls⟦br⟧
Were full of chinks and <qex>holes</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The priest took a chest, and bored a <qex>hole</qex> in the
lid.</q> <rj><qau>2 Kings xii. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An excavation in the ground, made by an animal to
live in, or a natural cavity inhabited by an animal; hence, a low,
narrow, or dark lodging or place; a mean habitation.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The foxes have <qex>holes</qex>, . . . but the Son of man hath not
where to lay his head.</q> <rj><qau>Luke ix. 58.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Games)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A small cavity used
in some games, usually one into which a marble or ball is to be played
or driven; hence, a score made by playing a marble or ball into such a
hole, as in golf.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Fives)</fld> <def>At Eton
College, England, that part of the floor of the court between the step
and the pepperbox.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Hollow; concavity; aperture; rent; fissure;
crevice; orifice; interstice; perforation; excavation; pit; cave; den;
cell.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hole and corner</b></col>, <cd>clandestine,
underhand.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧The wretched trickery of
<xex>hole</xex> and <xex>corner</xex> buffery.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Dickens.</au>
-- <col><b>Hole board</b></col> <fld>(Fancy Weaving)</fld>, <cd>a board
having holes through which cords pass which lift certain warp threads;
-- called also <altname>compass board</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 699 --></p>

<p><ent>Hole</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hole
<hw>Hole</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>holian</ets>. See <er>Hole</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To cut, dig, or bore a hole or holes in; <as>as, to <ex>hole</ex> a
post for the insertion of rails or bars</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To drive into a hole, as an animal, or a billiard
ball.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hole</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Hole
<hw>Hole</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To go or get into a hole.</def>
<rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hole in the air</ent>⟦br⟧
